<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h4 style="font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Item 8.01.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Other
Events.</font></b></h4>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Filed
as part of this Current Report on Form 8-K are the consolidated balance sheets
of Kraft Foods Inc. and subsidiaries as of December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004, and
the related consolidated statements of earnings, stockholders&#146; equity and cash
flows for each of the three years in the period ended December&nbsp;31, 2005
(the &#147;Financial Statements&#148;), the independent registered public accounting firm&#146;s
report thereon and the statement regarding computation of ratios of earnings to
fixed charges.&nbsp; The Financial Statements and the independent registered
public accounting firm&#146;s report will be incorporated by reference in Kraft
Foods Inc.&#146;s Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<h4 style="font-weight:bold;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-autospace:none;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Item 9.01.&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; Financial
Statements and Exhibits.</font></b></h4>

accounting firm&#146;s report thereon, are included herein.</font></p>

  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">282</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='8',FILE='C:\JMS\pgeetha\06-4341-1\task798927\4341-1-mm-01.htm',USER='Gpalavesam',CD='Feb  8 00:17 2006' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-decoration:underline;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 1.&#160; Background and Basis of Presentation:</font></u></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-decoration:none;">&nbsp;</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Background:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft Foods Inc. (&#147;Kraft&#148;) was incorporated in 2000 in the Commonwealth
of Virginia.&#160; Kraft, through its subsidiaries
(Kraft and its subsidiaries are hereinafter referred to as the &#147;Company&#148;), is
engaged in the manufacture and sale of packaged foods and beverages in the
United States, Canada, Europe, Latin America, Asia Pacific and Middle East and
Africa.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Prior to June&nbsp;13, 2001, the Company was a wholly-owned subsidiary
of Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#160; On June&nbsp;13,
2001, the Company completed an initial public offering (&#147;IPO&#148;) of 280,000,000
shares of its Class&nbsp;A common stock at a price of $31.00 per share.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2005, Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.
held 98.3% of the combined voting power of the Company&#146;s outstanding capital
stock and owned 87.2% of the outstanding shares of the Company&#146;s capital stock.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In June&nbsp;2005, the Company sold substantially all of its sugar
confectionery business for pre-tax proceeds of approximately $1.4 billion.&#160; The Company has reflected the results of its
sugar confectionery business prior to the closing date as discontinued
operations on the consolidated statements of earnings.&#160; The assets related to the sugar confectionery
business were reflected as assets of discontinued operations held for sale on
the consolidated balance sheet at December&nbsp;31, 2004.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In October&nbsp;2005,
the Company announced that, effective January&nbsp;1, 2006, its Canadian
business will be realigned to better integrate it into the Company&#146;s North
American business by product category.&#160;
Beginning in the first quarter of 2006, the operating results of the
Canadian business will be reported throughout the North American food segments.&#160; In addition, in the first quarter of 2006,
the Company&#146;s international businesses will be realigned to reflect the
reorganization announced within Europe in November&nbsp;2005.&#160; Beginning in the first quarter of 2006, the
operating results of the Company&#146;s international businesses will be reported in
two revised segments &#150; European Union; and to reflect increased management
attention to the reporting in the Company&#146;s developing markets - Developing
Markets, Oceania and North Asia.&#160;
Accordingly, prior period segment results will be restated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Basis of
presentation:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
consolidated financial statements include Kraft, as well as its wholly-owned
and majority-owned subsidiaries.&#160;
Investments in which the Company exercises significant influence (20% -
50% ownership interest) are accounted for under the equity method of
accounting.&#160; Investments in which the
Company has an ownership interest of less than 20%, or does not exercise
significant influence, are accounted for with the cost method of
accounting.&#160; All intercompany transactions
and balances between and among Kraft&#146;s subsidiaries have been eliminated.&#160; Transactions between any of the Company&#146;s
businesses and Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc. and its affiliates are included in these
financial statements.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles
generally accepted in the United States of America requires management to make
estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of assets and
liabilities, the disclosure of contingent liabilities at the dates of the
financial statements and the reported amounts of net revenues and expenses
during the reporting periods.&#160;
Significant estimates and assumptions include, among other things,
pension and benefit plan assumptions, lives and valuation assumptions of
goodwill and other intangible assets, marketing programs and income taxes.&#160; Actual results could differ from those
estimates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
operating subsidiaries generally report year-end results as of the Saturday
closest to the end of each year.&#160; This
resulted in fifty-three weeks of operating results in the Company&#146;s
consolidated statement</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">9</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='9',FILE='C:\JMS\pgeetha\06-4341-1\task798927\4341-1-mm-01.htm',USER='Gpalavesam',CD='Feb  8 00:17 2006' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">of earnings
for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2005, versus fifty-two weeks for the years
ended December&nbsp;31, 2004 and 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As discussed
in Note 13. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Income Taxes</font></i>, classification of certain
prior years&#146; amounts have been revised to conform with the current year&#146;s
presentation.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 2.&#160;
Summary of Significant Accounting Policies:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Cash and cash
equivalents:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Cash
equivalents include demand deposits with banks and all highly liquid
investments with original maturities of three months or less.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Depreciation,
amortization and goodwill valuation:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Property,
plant and equipment are stated at historical cost and depreciated by the
straight-line method over the estimated useful lives of the assets.&#160; Machinery and equipment are depreciated over
periods ranging from 3 to 20 years, and buildings and building improvements
over periods up to 40 years.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Definite life intangible
assets are amortized over their estimated useful lives.&#160; The Company is required to conduct an annual
review of goodwill and intangible assets for potential impairment.&#160; Goodwill impairment testing requires a
comparison between the carrying value and fair value of each reporting
unit.&#160; If the carrying value exceeds the
fair value, goodwill is considered impaired.&#160;
The amount of impairment loss is measured as the difference between the
carrying value and implied fair value of goodwill, which is determined using
discounted cash flows.&#160; Impairment
testing for non-amortizable intangible assets requires a comparison between the
fair value and carrying value of the intangible asset.&#160; If the carrying value exceeds fair value, the
intangible asset is considered impaired and is reduced to fair value.&#160; During the first quarter of 2005, the Company
completed its annual review of goodwill and intangible assets and no impairment
charges resulted from this review.&#160;
However, as part of the sale or pending sale of certain Canadian assets
and two brands, the Company recorded total non-cash pre-tax asset impairment
charges of $269 million in 2005, which included impairment of goodwill and
intangible assets of $13 million and $118 million, respectively, as well as
$138 million of asset write-downs.&#160;
During 2004, the Company&#146;s annual review of goodwill and intangible
assets resulted in a $29 million non-cash pre-tax charge related to an
intangible asset impairment for a small confectionery business in the United
States and certain brands in Mexico.&#160; A
portion of this charge, $12 million, was recorded as asset impairment and exit
costs on the consolidated statement of earnings.&#160; The remainder of the charge, $17 million, was
included in discontinued operations.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004, goodwill
by reportable segment was as follows (in millions):</font></p>

  </td>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Non-amortizable intangible
assets consist substantially of brand names purchased through the Nabisco
acquisition.&#160; Amortizable intangible
assets consist primarily of certain trademark licenses and non-compete agreements.&#160; Amortization expense for intangible assets
was $10 million, $11 million and $9 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160;
Amortization expense for each of the next five years is currently
estimated to be approximately $7 million or less.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The movement in goodwill and
gross carrying amount of intangible assets is as follows:</font></p>

  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

above, includes the reclassification to goodwill of certain amounts previously
classified as indefinite life intangible assets, as well as tax adjustments
related to the Nabisco acquisition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Environmental
costs:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company is
subject to laws and regulations relating to the protection of the
environment.&#160; The Company provides for
expenses associated with environmental remediation obligations on an
undiscounted basis when such amounts are probable and can be reasonably
estimated.&#160; Such accruals are adjusted as
new information develops or circumstances change.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">While it is
not possible to quantify with certainty the potential impact of actions
regarding environmental remediation and compliance efforts that the Company may
undertake in the future, in the opinion of management, environmental
remediation and compliance costs, before taking into account any recoveries</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">11</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">from third
parties, will not have a material adverse effect on the Company&#146;s consolidated
financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Foreign
currency translation:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company translates
the results of operations of its foreign subsidiaries using average exchange
rates during each period, whereas balance sheet accounts are translated using
exchange rates at the end of each period.&#160;
Currency translation adjustments are recorded as a component of
shareholders&#146; equity.&#160; Transaction gains
and losses are recorded in the consolidated statements of earnings and were not
significant for any of the periods presented.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Guarantees:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company accounts for
guarantees in accordance with Financial Accounting Standards Board (&#147;FASB&#148;)
Interpretation No.&nbsp;45, &#147;Guarantor&#146;s Accounting and Disclosure Requirements
for Guarantees, Including Indirect Guarantees of Indebtedness of Others.&#148;&#160; Interpretation No.&nbsp;45 requires the
disclosure of certain guarantees and the recognition of a liability for the
fair value of the obligation of qualifying guarantee activities.&#160; See Note 18.&#160;
<i><font style="font-style:italic;">Contingencies</font></i> for a
further discussion of guarantees.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Hedging
instruments:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Derivative
financial instruments are recorded at fair value on the consolidated balance
sheets as either assets or liabilities.&#160;
Changes in the fair value of derivatives are recorded each period either
in accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) or in earnings, depending
on whether a derivative is designated and effective as part of a hedge
transaction and, if it is, the type of hedge transaction.&#160; Gains and losses on derivative instruments
reported in accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses) are reclassified
to the consolidated statement of earnings in the periods in which operating
results are affected by the hedged item.&#160;
Cash flows from hedging instruments are classified in the same manner as
the affected hedged item in the consolidated statements of cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Impairment of
long-lived assets:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
reviews long-lived assets, including amortizable intangible assets, for
impairment whenever events or changes in business circumstances indicate that
the carrying amount of the assets may not be fully recoverable.&#160; The Company performs undiscounted operating
cash flow analyses to determine if an impairment exists.&#160; For purposes of recognition and measurement
of an impairment for assets held for use, the Company groups assets and
liabilities at the lowest level for which cash flows are separately
identifiable.&#160; If an impairment is
determined to exist, any related impairment loss is calculated based on fair
value.&#160; Impairment losses on assets to be
disposed of, if any, are based on the estimated proceeds to be received, less
costs of disposal.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Income taxes:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
accounts for income taxes in accordance with Statement of Financial Accounting
Standards (&#147;SFAS&#148;) No.&nbsp;109, &#147;Accounting for Income Taxes.&#148; The U.S.
accounts of the Company are included in the consolidated federal income tax return
of Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#160; Income taxes
are generally computed on a separate company basis.&#160; To the extent that foreign tax credits,
capital losses and other credits generated by the Company, which cannot
currently be utilized on a separate company basis, are utilized in Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#146;s
consolidated federal income tax return, the benefit is recognized in the
calculation of the Company&#146;s provision for income taxes.&#160; Based on the Company&#146;s current estimate, this
benefit is calculated to be approximately $225 million, $70 million and $100
million for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2005, 2004 and 2003,
respectively.&#160; The increase in 2005 is
driven primarily by dividend repatriations and certain legal entity
reorganizations.&#160; The Company makes
payments to, or is reimbursed by, Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc. for the tax effects
resulting from its inclusion in Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#146;s consolidated federal
income tax return, including current taxes payable and net changes in tax
provisions.&#160; Significant judgment is
required in determining</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">12</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='12',FILE='C:\JMS\pgeetha\06-4341-1\task798927\4341-1-mm-01.htm',USER='Gpalavesam',CD='Feb  8 00:17 2006' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">income tax
provisions and in evaluating tax positions.&#160;
The Company establishes additional provisions for income taxes when,
despite the belief that their tax positions are fully supportable, there remain
certain positions that are likely to be challenged and that may not be
sustained on review by tax authorities.&#160;
The Company evaluates and potentially adjusts these provisions in light
of changing facts and circumstances.&#160; The
consolidated tax provision includes the impact of changes to accruals that are
considered appropriate. Upon the closure of current and future tax audits in various
jurisdictions, significant income tax accrual reversals could continue to
occur, which could trigger reimbursements from Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Inventories:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Inventories
are stated at the lower of cost or market.&#160;
The last-in, first-out (&#147;LIFO&#148;) method is used to cost a majority of
domestic inventories.&#160; The cost of other
inventories is principally determined by the average cost method.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2004, the
FASB issued SFAS No.&nbsp;151, &#147;Inventory Costs.&#148;&#160; SFAS No.&nbsp;151 requires that abnormal idle
facility expense, spoilage, freight and handling costs be recognized as
current-period charges.&#160; In addition,
SFAS No.&nbsp;151 requires that allocation of fixed production overhead costs
to inventories be based on the normal capacity of the production facility.&#160; The Company is required to adopt the
provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;151 prospectively as of January&nbsp;1, 2006, but
the effect of adoption will not have a material impact on its consolidated
results of operations, financial position or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Marketing
costs:</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-autospace:none;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company promotes its products with
advertising, consumer incentives and trade promotions.&#160; Such programs include, but are not limited
to, discounts, coupons, rebates, in-store display incentives and volume-based
incentives.&#160; Advertising costs are
expensed as incurred.&#160; </font>Consumer incentive and trade promotion
activities are recorded as a reduction of revenues based on amounts estimated
as being due to customers and consumers at the end of a period, based
principally on historical utilization and redemption rates.&#160; For interim reporting purposes, advertising and
consumer incentive expenses are charged to operations as a percentage of
volume, based on estimated volume and related expense for the full year.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Revenue
recognition:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
recognizes revenues, net of sales incentives and including shipping and handling
charges billed to customers, upon shipment or delivery of goods when title and
risk of loss pass to customers.&#160; Shipping
and handling costs are classified as part of cost of sales.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Software
costs:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
capitalizes certain computer software and software development costs incurred
in connection with developing or obtaining computer software for internal
use.&#160; Capitalized software costs are
included in property, plant and equipment on the consolidated balance sheets
and amortized on a straight-line basis over the estimated useful lives of the
software, which do not exceed five years.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stock-based
compensation:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company accounts for employee stock compensation plans in
accordance with the intrinsic value-based method permitted by SFAS No.&nbsp;123,
&#147;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation,&#148; which has not resulted in
compensation cost for stock options.&#160; The
market value at date of grant of restricted stock and rights to receive shares
of stock is recorded as compensation expense over the period of restriction
(three years).</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2005, the Company had
stock-based employee compensation plans, which are described more fully in Note
11. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Stock Plans.&#160; </font></i>The Company applies the
recognition and measurement principles of Accounting Principles Board Opinion No.&nbsp;25,
&#147;Accounting for Stock Issued to Employees,&#148; and related Interpretations in
accounting for stock options within those plans.&#160; No compensation expense for employee</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">13</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">stock options is reflected in net earnings,
as all stock options granted under those plans had an exercise price equal to
the market value of the common stock on the date of grant.&#160; Net earnings, as reported, includes pre-tax
compensation expense related to restricted stock and rights to receive shares
of stock of $148 million, $106 million and $57 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160; The
following table illustrates the effect on net earnings and earnings per share (&#147;EPS&#148;)
if the Company had applied the fair value recognition provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;123
to measure compensation expense for outstanding stock option awards (using a

2004 and 2003 (in millions, except per share data):</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2004, the FASB issued
SFAS No.&nbsp;123 (revised 2004), &#147;Share-Based Payment&#148; (&#147;SFAS No.&nbsp;123R&#148;).&#160; SFAS No.&nbsp;123R requires companies to
measure compensation cost for share-based payments at fair value.&#160; The Company will adopt this new standard
prospectively, on January&nbsp;1, 2006, and the adoption of SFAS No.&nbsp;123R
will not have a material impact on its consolidated </font>financial position,
results of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 3.&#160;
Asset Impairment, Exit and Implementation Costs:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Restructuring Program:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 36.7pt;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In January&nbsp;2004, the Company announced a three-year restructuring
program with the objectives of leveraging the Company&#146;s global scale,
realigning and lowering its cost structure, and optimizing capacity
utilization.&#160; As part of this program,
the Company anticipates the closing or sale of up to 20 plants and the
elimination of approximately 6,000 positions.&#160;
From 2004 through 2006, the Company expects to incur approximately $1.2
billion in pre-tax charges, reflecting asset disposals, severance and other
implementation costs, including $297 million and $641 million incurred in 2005
and 2004, respectively.&#160; Approximately
60% of the pre-tax charges are expected to require cash payments.&#160; In addition, in January&nbsp;2006, the
Company announced plans to continue its restructuring efforts beyond those
originally contemplated.&#160; Additional
pre-tax charges are anticipated to be $2.5 billion from 2006 to 2009, of which
approximately $1.6 billion are expected to require cash payments.&#160; These charges will result in the anticipated
closure of up to 20 additional facilities and the elimination of approximately
8,000 additional positions.&#160; Initiatives
under the expanded program include additional organizational streamlining and
facility closures.&#160; The entire
restructuring program is expected to ultimately result in $3.7 billion in
pre-tax charges, the closure of up to</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">14</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">40 facilities
and the elimination of approximately 14,000 positions.&#160; Approximately $2.3 billion of the $3.7
billion in pre-tax charges are expected to require cash payments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Restructuring Costs:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2005 and 2004, pre-tax charges under the restructuring program
of $210 million and $583 million, respectively, were recorded as asset
impairment and exit costs on the consolidated statements of earnings.&#160; These pre-tax charges resulted from the
announcement of the closing of 19 plants since January&nbsp;2004, of which 6
occurred in 2005, the termination of co-manufacturing agreements in 2004, and
the continuation of a number of workforce reduction programs.&#160; Approximately $170 million of the pre-tax
charges incurred in 2005 will require cash payments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 36.7pt;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Pre-tax restructuring liability activity for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2005 and 2004, was as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="85%" style="border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:9.35pt;width:85.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="42%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:42.5%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Severance costs in the above schedule, which
relate to the workforce reduction programs, include the cost of related
benefits.&#160; Specific programs announced
during 2004 and 2005, as part of the overall restructuring program, will result
in the elimination of approximately 5,500 positions.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2005, approximately
4,900 of these positions have been eliminated.&#160;
Asset write-downs relate to the impairment of assets caused by the plant
closings and related activity.&#160; Other
costs incurred relate primarily to contract termination costs associated with
the plant closings and the termination of co-manufacturing and leasing
agreements.&#160; Severance charges taken
against assets relate to incremental pension costs, which reduce prepaid
pension assets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Implementation Costs:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-indent:9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2005 and 2004, the Company recorded
pre-tax implementation costs associated with the restructuring program.&#160; These costs include the discontinuance of
certain product lines and incremental costs related to the integration and
streamlining of functions and closure of facilities.&#160; Substantially all implementation costs
incurred in 2005 will require cash payments.&#160;
These costs were recorded on the consolidated statements of earnings as
follows:</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">15</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment Charges:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 36.7pt;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2005, the Company sold its fruit
snacks assets for approximately $30 million and incurred a pre-tax asset
impairment charge of $93 million in recognition of the sale.&#160; During December&nbsp;2005, the Company
reached agreements to sell certain assets in Canada and a small biscuit brand
in the U.S.&#160; These transactions are
expected to close in the first quarter of 2006.&#160;
The Company incurred pre-tax asset impairment charges of $176 million in
recognition of these pending sales.&#160;
These charges, which include the write-off of all associated intangible
assets, were recorded as asset impairment and exit costs on the consolidated
statement of earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2005, the Company completed its annual
review of goodwill and intangible assets and no charges resulted from this
review.&#160; During 2004, the Company
recorded non-cash pre-tax charges of $29 million related to an intangible asset
impairment for a small confectionery business in the United States and certain
brands in Mexico.&#160; A portion of this
charge, $17 million, was reclassified to earnings from discontinued operations
on the consolidated statement of earnings in the fourth quarter of 2004.&#160; The remaining charge was recorded as asset
impairment and exit costs on the consolidated statement of earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In November&nbsp;2004, following discussions
with the Company&#146;s joint venture partner in Turkey and an independent valuation
of its equity investment, it was determined that a permanent decline in value
had occurred. This valuation resulted in a $47 million non-cash pre-tax
charge.&#160; This charge was recorded as
marketing, administration and research costs on the consolidated statement of
earnings.&#160; During 2005, the Company&#146;s
interest in the joint venture was sold.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In June&nbsp;2005, the Company sold
substantially all of its sugar confectionery business for approximately $1.4
billion.&#160; In 2004, as a result of the
anticipated transaction, the Company recorded non-cash asset impairments
totaling $107 million.&#160; This charge was
included in loss from discontinued operations on the consolidated statement of
earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December&nbsp;2004, the Company announced
the sale of its yogurt brand, which closed in the first quarter of 2005.&#160; In 2004, as a result of the anticipated
transaction, the Company recorded asset impairments totaling $8 million.&#160; This charge was recorded as asset impairment
and exit costs on the consolidated statement of earnings.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">16</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

2005 and 2004, were included in the operating companies income of the following
segments:</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Other:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During
2003, the Company recorded a pre-tax charge of $6 million for asset impairment
and exit costs related to the closure of a Nordic snacks plant.&#160; This charge was included in the operating
companies income of the Europe, Middle East and Africa segment.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 4.&#160;
Related Party Transactions:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#146;s
subsidiary, Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc., provides the Company with
various services, including planning, legal, treasury, auditing, insurance,
human resources, office of the secretary, corporate affairs, information
technology, aviation and tax services.&#160;
Billings for these services, which were based on the cost to Altria
Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc. to provide such services and a management fee,
were $237 million, $310 million and $318 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160; The
Company performed at a similar cost various functions in 2005 that previously
had been provided by Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc., resulting in a lower
service charge in 2005.&#160; These costs were
paid to Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc. monthly.&#160; Although the cost of these services cannot be
quantified on a stand-alone basis, management has assessed that the billings
are reasonable based on the level of support provided by Altria Corporate
Services,&nbsp;Inc., and that they reflect all services provided.&#160; The cost and nature of the services are
reviewed annually by the Company&#146;s Audit Committee, which is comprised of
independent directors.&#160; The effects of
these transactions are included in operating cash flows in the Company&#146;s
consolidated statements of cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2005,
the Company repatriated certain foreign earnings as part of Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#146;s
dividend repatriation plan under provisions of the American Jobs Creation
Act.&#160; Increased taxes for this
repatriation of $21 million, were reimbursed by Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#160; The reimbursement was reported in the Company&#146;s
financial statements as an increase to additional paid-in capital.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December&nbsp;2005,
the Company purchased an airport hangar and certain personal property located
at the hangar in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, from Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc.
for an aggregate purchase price of approximately $3.3 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December&nbsp;2004,
the Company purchased two corporate aircraft from Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc.
for an aggregate purchase price of approximately $47 million.&#160; The Company also entered into an Aircraft
Management Agreement with Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc. in December&nbsp;2004,
pursuant to which Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc. agreed to perform
aircraft management, pilot services, maintenance and other aviation services
for the Company.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004,
Altria Corporate Services,&nbsp;Inc. provided to the Company certain financial
services, including payroll and accounts payable processing, at a cost of
approximately $25 million, which was included in the $310 million charge shown
above.&#160; In 2005, the Company performed
these functions for itself at a similar cost.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,
2005 and 2004, the Company had short-term amounts payable to Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.
of $652 million and $227 million, respectively.&#160;
The amounts payable to Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc. generally include accrued
dividends, taxes and service fees.&#160;
Interest on intercompany borrowings is based on the applicable London
Interbank Offered Rate.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The fair
values of the Company&#146;s short-term amounts due to Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc. and
affiliates approximate carrying amounts.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">18</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 5.&#160;
Divestitures:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Discontinued
Operations:</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In June&nbsp;2005,
the Company sold substantially all of its sugar confectionery business for
pre-tax proceeds of approximately $1.4 billion.&#160;
The sale included the <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Life Savers</font></i>, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Creme Savers</font></i>, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Altoids</font></i>, <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Trolli</font></i> and <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Sugus</font></i>
brands.&#160; The Company has reflected the
results of its sugar confectionery business prior to the closing date as
discontinued operations on the consolidated statements of earnings for all
years presented.&#160; Pursuant to the sugar
confectionery sale agreement, the Company has agreed to provide certain
transition and supply services to the buyer.&#160;
These service arrangements are primarily for terms of one year or less,
with the exception of one supply arrangement with a term of not more than three
years.&#160; The expected cash flow from this
supply arrangement is not significant.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Summary
results of operations for the sugar confectionery business were as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 35.3pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">investment in Turkey.&#160; The aggregate proceeds</font>  </font>received from these sales were $238 million,
on which the Company recorded pre-tax gains of $108 million. &#160;In December&nbsp;2005,
the Company announced the sale of certain Canadian assets and a small U.S.
biscuit brand, incurring pre-tax asset impairment charges of $176 million in recognition
of these sales.&#160; These transactions are
expected to close in the first quarter of 2006.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004,
the Company sold a Brazilian snack nuts business and trademarks associated with
a candy business in Norway.&#160; The
aggregate proceeds received from the sale of these businesses were $18 million,
on which pre-tax losses of $3 million were recorded.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2003, the Company sold a European rice business and a branded
fresh cheese business in Italy. The aggregate proceeds received from sales of
businesses were $96 million, on which the Company recorded pre-tax gains of $31
million.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The operating
results of the other divestitures, discussed above, in the aggregate, were not
material to the Company&#146;s consolidated financial position, results of operations
or cash flows in any of the periods presented.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 6.&#160;
Acquisitions:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2004, the Company acquired a U.S.-based beverage business for a
total cost of $137 million.&#160; During 2003,
the Company acquired a biscuits business in Egypt, trademarks associated with a
small U.S.-based natural foods business and other smaller acquisitions for a
total cost of $98 million.&#160; The effects
of these acquisitions were not material to the Company&#146;s consolidated financial
position, results of operations or cash flows in any of the periods presented.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 7.&#160;
Inventories: </font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The cost of
approximately 40% and 37% of inventories in 2005 and 2004, respectively, was
determined using the LIFO method.&#160; The
stated LIFO amounts of inventories were approximately $71 million and $81
million higher than the current cost of inventories at December&nbsp;31, 2005
and 2004, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 8.&#160;

2005 and 2004, the Company&#146;s short-term borrowings and related average interest
rates consisted of the following:</font></p>

<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company maintains revolving credit facilities that have historically been used
to support the issuance of commercial paper.&#160;
In April&nbsp;2005, the Company terminated its $2.0 billion, multi-year
revolving credit facility expiring in July&nbsp;2006 and its $2.5 billion, 364-day
revolving credit facility expiring in July&nbsp;2005 and replaced them with a
new $4.5 billion, multi-year revolving credit facility that expires in April&nbsp;2010.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2005, the credit line
for the Company and the related activity were as follows (in billions of
dollars):</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

</div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company&#146;s revolving credit facility, which is for its sole use, requires the
maintenance of a minimum net worth of $20.0 billion.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2005, the Company&#146;s net
worth was $29.6 billion.&#160; The Company
expects to continue to meet this covenant.&#160;
The revolving credit facility does not include any other financial
tests, any credit rating triggers or any provisions that could require the
posting of collateral.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
addition to the above, certain international subsidiaries of Kraft maintain
credit lines to meet the short-term working capital needs of the international
businesses.&#160; These credit lines, which
amounted to approximately $1.3 billion as of December&nbsp;31, 2005, are for
the sole use of the Company&#146;s international businesses.&#160; Borrowings on these lines amounted to
approximately $400 million and $150 million at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004,
respectively. </font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 9.&#160;
Long-Term Debt:</font></u></p>

2005 and 2004, the Company&#146;s long-term debt consisted of the following:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Aggregate
maturities of long-term debt are as follows (in millions):</font></p>

<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Based on
market quotes, where available, or interest rates currently available to the
Company for issuance of debt with similar terms and remaining maturities, the
aggregate fair value of the Company&#146;s long-term debt, including the current
portion of long-term debt, was $9,945 million and $11,017 million at December&nbsp;31,
2005 and 2004, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 10.&#160;

articles of incorporation authorize 3.0 billion shares of Class&nbsp;A common
stock, 2.0 billion shares of Class&nbsp;B common stock and 500 million shares
of preferred stock.&#160; Shares of Class&nbsp;A

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft
repurchases its Class&nbsp;A common stock in open market transactions.&#160; During December&nbsp;2004, the Company began
a $1.5 billion two-year share repurchase program.&#160; During 2005, the Company repurchased 39.2
million shares of its Class&nbsp;A common stock at a cost of $1.2 billion, an
average price of $30.65 per share.&#160; As of
December&nbsp;31, 2005, the Company had repurchased 40.6 million shares of its Class&nbsp;A
common stock, under its $1.5 billion authority, at an aggregate cost of $1.25
billion.&#160; During December&nbsp;2004,
Kraft completed its multi-year $700 million Class&nbsp;A common stock
repurchase program, acquiring 21,718,847 Class&nbsp;A shares at an average
price of $32.23 per share.&#160; During December&nbsp;2003,
Kraft completed its $500 million Class&nbsp;A common stock repurchase program,
acquiring 15,308,458 Class&nbsp;A shares at an average price of $32.66 per
share.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Class&nbsp;B
common shares issued and outstanding at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004 were
1.18 billion.&#160; Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.
holds 276.5 million Class&nbsp;A common shares and all of the Class&nbsp;B
common shares at December&nbsp;31, 2005.&#160;
There are no preferred shares issued and outstanding.&#160; Class&nbsp;A common shares are entitled to
one vote each, while Class&nbsp;B common shares are entitled to ten votes
each.&#160; Therefore, Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.
holds 98.3% of the combined voting power of the Company&#146;s outstanding capital
stock at December&nbsp;31, 2005.&#160; At </font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">22</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">December&nbsp;31,
2005, 170,243,228 shares of common stock were reserved for stock options and
other stock awards.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 11.&#160;
Stock Plans:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2005, the
Company&#146;s Board of Directors adopted, and the stockholders approved, the Kraft
2005 Performance Incentive Plan (the &#147;2005 Plan&#148;).&#160; The 2005 Plan replaced the Company&#146;s 2001
Performance Incentive Plan (the &#147;2001 Plan&#148;).&#160;
Under the 2005 Plan, the Company may grant to eligible employees awards
of stock options, stock appreciation rights, restricted stock, restricted and
deferred stock units, and other awards based on the Company&#146;s Class&nbsp;A
common stock, as well as performance-based annual and long-term incentive
awards.&#160; A maximum of 150 million shares
of the Company&#146;s Class&nbsp;A common stock may be issued under the 2005 Plan,
of which no more than 45 million shares may be awarded as restricted
stock.&#160; In addition, the Company may
grant up to 500,000 shares of Class&nbsp;A common stock to members of the Board
of Directors who are not full-time employees of the Company or Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.,
or their subsidiaries, under the Kraft Directors Plan (the &#147;2001 Directors Plan&#148;).&#160; Shares available to be granted under the 2005
Plan and the 2001 Directors Plan at December&nbsp;31, 2005, were 149,879,210
and 439,367, respectively. &#160;Restricted
shares available for grant under the 2005 Plan at December&nbsp;31, 2005, were
44,879,210.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
applies the intrinsic value-based methodology in accounting for the various
stock plans.&#160; Accordingly, no
compensation expense has been recognized other than for restricted stock
awards.&#160; In 2004, the FASB issued SFAS No.&nbsp;123
(revised 2004), &#147;Share-Based Payment&#148; (&#147;SFAS No.&nbsp;123R&#148;).&#160; SFAS No.&nbsp;123R requires companies to
measure compensation cost for share-based payments at fair value.&#160; The Company will adopt this new standard
prospectively, on January&nbsp;1, 2006, and the adoption of SFAS No.&nbsp;123R
will not have a material impact on its consolidated financial position, results
of operations or cash flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stock option
activity was as follows for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2003, 2004 and
2005:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Prior to the
IPO, certain employees of the Company participated in Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.&#146;s
stock compensation plans.&#160; Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.
does not intend to issue additional Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc. stock compensation
to the Company&#146;s employees, except for reloads of previously issued
options.&#160; Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc.
accounts for its plans in accordance with the intrinsic value-based method
permitted by SFAS No.&nbsp;123, &#147;Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation,&#148;
which did not result in compensation cost for stock options.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
employees held options to purchase the following number of shares of Altria
Group,&nbsp;Inc. stock at December&nbsp;31, 2005:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31,
2004 and 2003, the Company&#146;s employees held options to purchase the following
number of shares of Altria Group,&nbsp;Inc. stock: 29,487,149 shares at an
average exercise price of $38.38 per share at December&nbsp;31, 2004; and
39,241,651 shares at an average exercise price of $37.25 per share at December&nbsp;31,
2003.&#160; Of these amounts, the following
were exercisable at each date: 29,033,020 at an average exercise price of
$38.19 per share at December&nbsp;31, 2004; and 39,025,325 at an average
exercise price of $37.19 per share at December&nbsp;31, 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Had
compensation cost for stock option awards under the Kraft plans and Altria
Group,&nbsp;Inc. plans been determined by using the fair value at the grant
date, the Company&#146;s net earnings and basic and diluted EPS would have been
$2,625 million, $1.56 and $1.55, respectively, for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
2005; $2,658 million, $1.56 and $1.55, respectively, for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
2004; and $3,464 million, $2.01 and $2.00, respectively, for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
2003.&#160; The foregoing impact of
compensation cost was determined using a modified Black-Scholes methodology and
the following assumptions:</font></p>
