<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company may grant shares of restricted
stock and rights to receive shares of stock to eligible employees, giving them
in most instances all of the rights of stockholders, except that they may not
sell, assign, pledge or otherwise encumber such shares and rights.&#160; Such shares and rights are subject to
forfeiture if certain employment conditions are not met.&#160; During 2005, 2004 and 2003, the Company granted
approximately 4.2 million, 4.1 million and 3.7 million restricted Class&nbsp;A
shares, respectively, to eligible U.S.-based employees, and during 2005, 2004
and 2003, also issued to eligible non-U.S. employees rights to receive
approximately 1.8 million, 1.9 million and 1.6 million Class&nbsp;A equivalent
shares, respectively.&#160; The market value
per restricted share or right was $33.32, $32.23 and $36.56 on the dates of the
2005, 2004 and 2003 grants, respectively.&#160;
At December&nbsp;31, 2005, restrictions on these shares and rights, net
of forfeitures, lapse as follows:&#160; 2006 &#150;
4,140,552 shares; 2007 &#150; 5,079,097 shares; 2008 &#150; 5,596,297 shares; 2009 &#150;
100,000 shares; 2010 &#150; 69,170 shares; and 2012 &#150; 100,000 shares.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The fair value of the shares of restricted
stock and rights to receive shares of stock at the date of grant is amortized
to expense ratably over the restriction period.&#160;
The Company recorded compensation expense related to the restricted
stock and rights of $148 million, $106 million and $57 million for the years
ended December&nbsp;31, 2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160; The unamortized portion, which is reported on
the consolidated balance sheets as a reduction of shareholders&#146; equity, was
$202 million and $190 million at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 12.&#160;
Earnings Per Share:</font></u></p>

diluted EPS from continuing and discontinued operations were calculated using
the following:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Incremental
shares from assumed conversions are calculated as the number of shares that
would be issued, net of the number of shares that could be purchased in the
marketplace with the cash received upon stock option exercise or, in the case
of restricted stock and rights, the number of shares corresponding to the
unamortized compensation expense.&#160; For
2005 and 2004, the number of stock options excluded from the </font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">25</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">calculation of
weighted average shares for diluted EPS because their effects were antidilutive
(i.e. the cash that would be received upon exercise is greater than the average
market price of the stock during the period) was immaterial.&#160; For the 2003 computation, 18 million Class&nbsp;A
common stock options were excluded from the calculation of weighted average
shares for diluted EPS because their effects were antidilutive.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

interest, and provision for income taxes consisted of the following for the
years ended December&nbsp;31, 2005, 2004 and 2003:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The loss from discontinued operations for the year ended December&nbsp;31,
2005, includes additional tax expense of $280 million from the sale of the
sugar confectionery business.&#160; The loss
from discontinued operations for the year ended December&nbsp;31, 2004,
included a deferred income tax benefit of $43 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2005, applicable United States federal income
taxes and foreign withholding taxes have not been provided on approximately
$3.6 billion of accumulated earnings of foreign subsidiaries that are expected
to be permanently reinvested.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
October&nbsp;2004, the American Jobs Creation Act (&#147;the Jobs Act&#148;) was signed
into law.&#160; The Jobs Act includes a
deduction for 85% of certain foreign earnings that are repatriated.&#160; </font>In 2005, the Company repatriated
approximately $500 million of earnings under the provisions of the Jobs
Act.&#160; Deferred taxes had previously been
provided for a portion of the dividends to be remitted.&#160; The reversal of the deferred taxes more than
offset the tax costs to repatriate the earnings and resulted in a net tax
reduction of $28 million in the consolidated income tax provision during 2005,
the majority of which was recorded during the second quarter.</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;">&nbsp;</p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Jobs Act also provides tax relief to U.S. domestic manufacturers by providing a
tax deduction related to a percentage of the lesser of &#147;qualified production
activities income&#148; or taxable income.&#160;
The deduction, </font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">26</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">which was 3% in 2005,
increases to 9% by 2010.&#160; In accordance
with SFAS No.&nbsp;109, the Company will recognize these benefits in the year
earned.&#160; The tax benefit in 2005 was
approximately $25 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The tax rate in 2005 includes the settlement of an outstanding U.S. tax
claim of $24 million in the second quarter; $82 million from the resolution of
outstanding items in the Company&#146;s international operations, the majority of
which was in the first quarter, and $33 million of tax impacts associated with
the sale of a U.S. biscuit brand.&#160; The
2005 rate also includes a $53 million aggregate benefit from the domestic
manufacturers&#146; deduction provision and the dividend repatriation provision of
the Jobs Act.&#160; The tax provision in 2004
includes an $81 million favorable resolution of an outstanding tax item, the
majority of which occurred in the third quarter of 2004, and the reversal of
$35 million of tax accruals that were no longer required due to tax events that
occurred during the first quarter of 2004.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company is regularly audited by federal, state and foreign tax
authorities, and these audits are at various stages at any given time.&#160; The Company anticipates several domestic and
foreign audits will close in 2006 with favorable settlements.&#160; Any tax contingency reserves in excess of
additional assessed liabilities will be reversed at the time the audits close.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The tax effects of temporary differences that gave rise to deferred
income tax assets and liabilities consisted of the following at December&nbsp;31,
2005 and 2004:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">To conform with the current year&#146;s presentation, the amounts shown
above at December&nbsp;31, 2004 have been revised from previously reported
amounts to reflect state deferred tax amounts that were previously included in
other liabilities on the consolidated balance sheet.&#160; As a result, deferred income tax liabilities
on </font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">27</font></p>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='27',FILE='C:\JMS\tvenkatesh\06-4341-1\task798413\4341-1-mm-03.htm',USER='tgkandaswamy',CD='Feb  7 21:43 2006' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 34.55pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">the December&nbsp;31,
2004 consolidated balance sheet increased $618 million from $5,850 million to
$6,468 million, with a corresponding reduction in other liabilities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 14.&#160;
Segment Reporting:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt 36.7pt;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company manufactures and markets packaged food products, consisting
principally of beverages, cheese, snacks, convenient meals and various packaged
grocery products.&#160; Kraft manages and
reports operating results through two units, Kraft North America Commercial and
Kraft International Commercial.&#160;
Reportable segments for Kraft North America Commercial are organized and
managed principally by product category.&#160;
Kraft North America Commercial&#146;s segments are </font>U.S. Beverages; U.S. Cheese, Canada&nbsp;&amp;
North America Foodservice; U.S. Convenient Meals; U.S. Grocery; and U.S. Snacks&nbsp;&amp;
Cereals. Kraft International Commercial&#146;s operations are organized and
managed by geographic location.&#160; Kraft
International Commercial&#146;s segments are Europe, Middle East&nbsp;&amp; Africa;
and Latin America&nbsp;&amp; Asia Pacific.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
October&nbsp;2005, the Company announced that, effective January&nbsp;1, 2006,
its Canadian business will be realigned to better integrate it into the Company&#146;s
North American business by product category.&#160;
Beginning in the first quarter of 2006, the operating results of the
Canadian business will be reported throughout the North American food
segments.&#160; </font>In addition, in the
first quarter of 2006, the Company&#146;s international businesses will be realigned
to reflect the reorganization announced within Europe in November&nbsp;2005.&#160; Beginning in the first quarter of 2006, the
operating results of the Company&#146;s international businesses will be reported in
two revised segments &#151; European Union; and to reflect increased management
attention to the reporting in the Company&#146;s developing markets &#151; Developing
Markets, Oceania and North Asia.&#160;
Accordingly, prior period segment results will be restated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s management uses operating companies income, which is
defined as operating income before general corporate expenses and amortization
of intangibles, to evaluate segment performance and allocate resources.&#160; Management believes it is appropriate to
disclose this measure to help investors analyze the business performance and
trends of the various business segments.&#160;
Interest and other debt expense, net, and provision for income taxes are
centrally managed and, accordingly, such items are not presented by segment
since they are not included in the measure of segment profitability reviewed by
management.&#160; The Company&#146;s assets, which
are principally in the United States and Europe, are managed geographically.&#160; The accounting policies of the segments are
the same as those described in Note 2. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Summary of Significant
Accounting Policies</font></i>.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">28</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.36%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">5,195</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 36.7pt;text-indent:-27.35pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
largest customer, Wal-Mart Stores,&nbsp;Inc. and its affiliates, accounted for
approximately 14%, 14% and 12% of consolidated net revenues for 2005, 2004 and
2003, respectively.&#160; These net revenues
occurred primarily in the United States and were across all segments.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">29</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='30',FILE='C:\JMS\tvenkatesh\06-4341-1\task798413\4341-1-mm-03.htm',USER='tgkandaswamy',CD='Feb  7 21:43 2006' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div style="font-family:Times New Roman;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Items
affecting the comparability of the Company&#146;s continuing operating results were
as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><i><font style="font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment, Exit and
Implementation Costs &#151;</font></i> As
discussed in Note 3. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment, Exit
and Implementation Costs</font></i>, the Company recorded charges for these
items of $566 million, $700 million and $6 million for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160; See
Note 3 for the breakdown of these pre-tax charges by segment.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="3" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:12.0pt;">&#149;</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font><i><font style="font-style:italic;">(Gains) Losses on Sales of Businesses
&#151;</font></i> During 2005, the Company
sold its fruit snacks assets, U.K. desserts assets, U.S. yogurt brand, a small
business in Colombia, a minor trademark in Mexico and a small equity investment
in Turkey for aggregate pre-tax gains of $108 million.&#160; During 2004, the Company sold a Brazilian
snack nuts business and trademarks associated with a candy business in Norway
for aggregate pre-tax losses of $3 million.&#160;
During 2003, the Company sold a European rice business and a branded
fresh cheese business in Italy for aggregate pre-tax gains of $31 million.&#160; These pre-tax (gains) losses were included in
the operating companies income of the following segments:</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 9.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 15.&#160;
Benefit Plans:</font></u></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company sponsors noncontributory defined benefit pension plans covering
substantially all U.S. employees.&#160;
Pension coverage for employees of the Company&#146;s non-U.S. subsidiaries is
provided, to the extent deemed appropriate, through separate plans, many of
which are governed by local statutory requirements.&#160; In addition, the Company&#146;s U.S. and Canadian
subsidiaries provide health care and other benefits to substantially all
retired employees.&#160; Health care benefits
for retirees outside the United States and Canada are generally covered through
local government plans.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
plan assets and benefit obligations of the Company&#146;s U.S. and Canadian pension
plans are measured at December&nbsp;31 of each year and all other non-U.S.
pension plans are measured at September&nbsp;30 of each year.&#160; The benefit obligations of the Company&#146;s
postretirement plans are measured at December&nbsp;31 of each year.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">33</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
combined U.S. and non-U.S. pension plans resulted in a net prepaid pension
asset of $2,385 million and $2,404 million at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004,
respectively.&#160; These amounts were
recognized in the Company&#146;s consolidated balance sheets at December&nbsp;31,
2005 and 2004, as prepaid pension assets of $3,617 million and $3,569 million,
respectively, for those plans in which plan assets exceeded their accumulated
benefit obligations, and as other liabilities of $1,232 million and $1,165
million, respectively, for plans in which the accumulated benefit obligations
exceeded their plan assets.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">34</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For
U.S. and non-U.S. pension plans, the change in the additional minimum liability
in 2005 and 2004 was as follows:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
accumulated benefit obligation, which represents benefits earned to date, for
the U.S. pension plans was $5,580 million and $5,327 million at December&nbsp;31,
2005 and 2004, respectively.&#160; The
accumulated benefit obligation for the non-U.S. pension plans was $3,494
million and $3,251 million at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004, respectively.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2005
and 2004, certain of the Company&#146;s U.S. pension plans were underfunded, with
projected benefit obligations, accumulated benefit obligations and the fair
value of plan assets of $268 million, $211 million and $14 million,
respectively, in 2005, and $260 million, $188 million and $11 million,
respectively, in 2004.&#160; The majority of
these relate to plans for salaried employees that cannot be funded under IRS
regulations.&#160; For certain non-U.S. plans,
which have accumulated benefit obligations in excess of plan assets, the
projected benefit obligation, accumulated benefit obligation and fair value of
plan assets were $2,134 million, $1,993 million and $1,088 million,
respectively, as of December&nbsp;31, 2005, and $2,012 million, $1,877 million
and $950 million, respectively, as of December&nbsp;31, 2004.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
following weighted-average assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s
benefit obligations under the plans at December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <td width="12%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">4.00</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">4.00</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.11</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.11</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.22%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company&#146;s 2005 year end U.S. and Canadian plans discount rates were developed
from a model portfolio of high quality, fixed-income debt instruments with
durations that match the expected future cash flows of the benefit
obligations.&#160; The 2005 year end discount
rates for the Company&#146;s non-U.S. plans were developed from local bond indices
that match local benefit obligations as closely as possible.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">35</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Components
of Net Periodic Benefit Cost</font></b></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-align:left;text-indent:-45.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">During 2005,
employees left the Company under workforce reduction programs, resulting in
settlement losses of $10 million for the U.S. plans.&#160; In addition, retiring employees elected
lump-sum payments, resulting in settlement losses of $73 million, $41 million
and $51 million in 2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.&#160; Non-U.S. plant closures and early retirement
benefits resulted in curtailment and settlement losses of $25 million and $7
million in 2005 and 2004, respectively.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
following weighted-average assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s net
pension cost for the years ended December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="8%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:8.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.11</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="8%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:8.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3.12</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company&#146;s expected rate of return on plan assets is determined by the plan
assets&#146; historical long-term investment performance, current asset allocation
and estimates of future long-term returns by asset class.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft and
certain of its subsidiaries sponsor employee savings plans, to which the
Company contributes. These plans cover certain salaried, non-union and union
employees.&#160; The Company&#146;s contributions
and costs are determined by the matching of employee contributions, as defined
by the plans.&#160; Amounts charged to expense
for defined contribution plans totaled $94 million, $92 million and $84 million
in 2005, 2004 and 2003, respectively.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">36</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>

  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">100</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 1.5pt 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">%</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:left;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company&#146;s investment strategy is based on an expectation that equity securities
will outperform debt securities over the long term.&#160; Accordingly, the composition of the Company&#146;s
U.S. plan assets is broadly characterized as a 70%/30% allocation between
equity and debt securities.&#160; The strategy
utilizes indexed U.S. equity securities, actively managed international equity
securities and actively managed investment grade debt securities (which
constitute 80% or more of debt securities) with lesser allocations to high
yield and international debt securities.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">For
the plans outside the U.S., the investment strategy is subject to local
regulations and the asset/liability profiles of the plans in each individual
country.&#160; These specific circumstances
result in a level of equity exposure that is typically less than the U.S.
plans.&#160; In aggregate, the actual asset
allocations of the non-U.S. plans are virtually identical to their respective
asset policy targets.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Company attempts to mitigate investment risk by rebalancing between equity and
debt asset classes as the Company&#146;s contributions and monthly benefit payments
are made.</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company presently makes,
and plans to make, contributions, to the extent that they do not generate an
excise tax liability, in order to maintain plan assets in excess of the
accumulated benefit obligation of its funded U.S. and non-U.S. plans.&#160; Currently, the Company anticipates making
contributions of approximately $140 million in 2006 to its U.S. plans and
approximately $106 million in 2006 to its non-U.S. plans, based on current tax
law.&#160; However, these estimates are
subject to change as a result of many factors, including changes in tax and
other benefit laws, as well as asset performance significantly above or below
the assumed long-term rate of return on pension assets, or significant changes
in interest rates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .3in;text-align:left;text-indent:-.3in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
estimated future benefit payments from the Company&#146;s pension plans at December&nbsp;31,
2005, were as follows:</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Postretirement
Benefit Plans</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Net
postretirement health care costs consisted of the following for the years ended
December&nbsp;31, 2005, 2004 and 2003:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In December&nbsp;2003, the
United States enacted into law the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement and
Modernization Act of 2003 (the &#147;Act&#148;).&#160;
The Act establishes a prescription drug benefit under Medicare, known as
&#147;Medicare Part&nbsp;D,&#148; and a federal subsidy to sponsors of retiree health
care benefit plans that provide a benefit that is at least actuarially
equivalent to Medicare Part&nbsp;D.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In May&nbsp;2004, the FASB
issued FASB Staff Position No.&nbsp;106-2, &#147;Accounting and Disclosure
Requirements Related to the Medicare Prescription Drug, Improvement and
Modernization Act of 2003&#148; (&#147;FSP 106-2&#148;).&#160;
FSP 106-2 requires companies to account for the effect of the subsidy on
benefits attributable to past service as an actuarial experience gain and as a
reduction of the service cost component of net postretirement health care costs
for amounts attributable to current service, if the benefit provided is at
least actuarially equivalent to Medicare Part&nbsp;D.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company adopted FSP 106-2
in the third quarter of 2004.&#160; The impact
for 2005 and 2004 was a reduction of pre-tax net postretirement health care
costs and an increase in net earnings.&#160;
The amounts in the table above reflect the following benefits:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="75%" style="border-collapse:collapse;margin-left:.5in;width:75.0%;">
 <tr>

  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="13" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:9.6pt;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="51" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:38.6pt;">
  <p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">2005</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="13" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:9.6pt;">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition, as of July&nbsp;1,
2004, the Company reduced its accumulated postretirement benefit obligation for
the subsidy related to benefits attributed to past service by $315 million and
decreased its unrecognized actuarial losses by the same amount.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
following weighted-average assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s net
postretirement cost for the years ended December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

  </td>

  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">

<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In 2006, the
discount rate used to determine the Company&#146;s net postretirement cost will be
5.60% for its U.S. plans and 5.00% for its Canadian plans, and the health care
cost trend rate will be 8.00% for its U.S. plans and 9.00% for its Canadian
plans.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
postretirement health care plans are not funded.&#160; The changes in the accumulated benefit
obligation and net amount accrued at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004, were as
follows:</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The current
portion of the Company&#146;s accrued postretirement health care costs of $208
million and $217 million at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004, respectively, is
included in other accrued liabilities on the consolidated balance sheets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="left" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-align:left;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
following weighted-average assumptions were used to determine the Company&#146;s
postretirement benefit obligations at December&nbsp;31:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Postemployment
Benefit Plans</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft and
certain of its affiliates sponsor postemployment benefit plans covering
substantially all salaried and certain hourly employees.&#160; The cost of these plans is charged to expense
over the working life of the covered employees.&#160;
Net postemployment costs consisted of the following for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2005, 2004 and 2003:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">6</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in .7pt 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As previously
discussed in Note 3. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment, Exit and
Implementation Costs</font></i>, the Company announced several workforce
reduction programs during 2005 and 2004 as part of the overall restructuring
program.&#160; The cost of these programs,
$139 million and $167 million in 2005 and 2004, respectively, is included in
other expense, above.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company&#146;s
postemployment plans are not funded.&#160; The
changes in the benefit obligations of the plans at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and
2004, were as follows:</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='40',FILE='C:\JMS\tvenkatesh\06-4341-1\task798413\4341-1-mm-03.htm',USER='tgkandaswamy',CD='Feb  7 21:43 2006' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .75in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
accumulated benefit obligation was determined using an assumed ultimate annual
turnover rate of 0.3% in 2005 and 2004, assumed compensation cost increases of
4.0% in 2005 and 2004, and assumed benefits as defined in the respective
plans.&#160; Postemployment costs arising from
actions that offer employees benefits in excess of those specified in the
respective plans are charged to expense when incurred.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 16.&#160;
Additional Information:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The amounts shown below are for continuing
operations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 17. Financial Instruments:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Derivative financial instruments</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
operates globally, with manufacturing and sales facilities in various locations
around the world, and utilizes certain financial instruments to manage its
foreign currency and commodity exposures.&#160;
Derivative financial instruments are used by the Company, principally to
reduce exposures to market risks resulting from fluctuations in foreign
exchange rates and commodity prices by creating offsetting exposures.&#160; The Company is not a party to leveraged
derivatives and, by policy, does not use financial instruments for speculative
purposes.&#160; Financial instruments
qualifying for hedge accounting must maintain a specified level of effectiveness
between the hedging instrument and the item being hedged, both at</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">41</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='41',FILE='C:\JMS\tvenkatesh\06-4341-1\task798413\4341-1-mm-03.htm',USER='tgkandaswamy',CD='Feb  7 21:43 2006' -->


<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">


<div>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">KRAFT FOODS INC. and SUBSIDIARIES</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">NOTES to CONSOLIDATED FINANCIAL STATEMENTS</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 36.7pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">inception and
throughout the hedged period.&#160; The
Company formally documents the nature of and relationships between the hedging
instruments and hedged items, as well as its risk-management objectives,
strategies for undertaking the various hedge transactions and method of
assessing hedge effectiveness.&#160;
Additionally, for hedges of forecasted transactions, the significant
characteristics and expected terms of the forecasted transaction must be
specifically identified, and it must be probable that each forecasted transaction
will occur.&#160; If it were deemed probable
that the forecasted transaction will not occur, the gain or loss would be
recognized in earnings currently.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company
uses forward foreign exchange contracts and foreign currency options to
mitigate its exposure to changes in exchange rates from third-party and
intercompany actual and forecasted transactions.&#160; Substantially all of the Company&#146;s derivative
financial instruments are effective as hedges.&#160;
The primary currencies to which the Company is exposed, based on the
size and location of its businesses, include the euro, Swiss franc, British
pound and Canadian dollar.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,
2005 and 2004, the Company had foreign exchange option and forward contracts
with aggregate notional amounts of $2.2 billion and $2.9 billion,
respectively.&#160; The effective portion of
unrealized gains and losses associated with forward and option contracts is
deferred as a component of accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses)
until the underlying hedged transactions are reported on the Company&#146;s consolidated
statement of earnings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company is
exposed to price risk related to forecasted purchases of certain commodities
used as raw materials by its businesses.&#160;
Accordingly, the Company uses commodity forward contracts as cash flow
hedges, primarily for coffee and cocoa.&#160;
Commodity futures and options are also used to hedge the price of
certain commodities, including milk, coffee, cocoa, wheat, corn, sugar and
soybean oil.&#160; In general, commodity
forward contracts qualify for the normal purchase exception under SFAS No.&nbsp;133
and are, therefore, not subject to the provisions of SFAS No.&nbsp;133.&#160; At December&nbsp;31, 2005 and 2004, the
Company had net long commodity positions of $521 million and $443 million,
respectively.&#160; Unrealized gains or losses
on net commodity positions were immaterial at December&nbsp;31, 2005 and
2004.&#160; The effective portion of
unrealized gains and losses on commodity futures and option contracts is
deferred as a component of accumulated other comprehensive earnings (losses)
and is recognized as a component of cost of sales in the Company&#146;s consolidated
statement of earnings when the related inventory is sold.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Ineffectiveness
related to cash flow hedges was not material for the years ended December&nbsp;31,
2005, 2004 and 2003.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,
2005, the Company was hedging forecasted transactions for periods not exceeding
the next fifteen months.&#160; At December&nbsp;31,
2005, the Company estimates that derivative losses of approximately $2 million,
net of income taxes, reported in accumulated other comprehensive earnings
(losses) will be reclassified to the consolidated statement of earnings within
the next twelve months.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">42</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

</div>

  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(4</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 1.5pt 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">)</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.3%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">6</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.3%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" style="border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">1</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Credit exposure and credit risk</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Company is
exposed to credit loss in the event of nonperformance by counterparties.&#160; However, the Company does not anticipate
nonperformance, and such exposure was not material at December&nbsp;31, 2005.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Fair value</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .25in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The aggregate
fair value, based on market quotes, of the Company&#146;s third-party debt at December&nbsp;31,
2005, was $10,750 million as compared with its carrying value of $10,548
million.&#160; The aggregate fair value of the
Company&#146;s third-party debt at December&nbsp;31, 2004, was $12,835 million as
compared with its carrying value of $12,291 million.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">See Notes 4, 8
and 9 for additional disclosures of fair value for short-term borrowings and
long-term debt.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 18.&#160;
Contingencies</font></u>:</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kraft and its
subsidiaries are parties to a variety of legal proceedings arising out of the
normal course of business, including a few cases in which substantial amounts
of damages are sought.&#160; While the results
of litigation cannot be predicted with certainty, management believes that the
final outcome of these proceedings will not have a material adverse effect on
the Company&#146;s consolidated financial position, results of operations or cash
flows.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Third-Party Guarantees</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 45.0pt;text-indent:-.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">At December&nbsp;31, 2005,
the Company&#146;s third-party guarantees, which are primarily derived from
acquisition and divestiture activities, approximated $27 million.&#160; Substantially all of these guarantees expire
through 2013, with $14 million expiring during 2006.&#160; The Company is required to perform under
these guarantees in the event that a third party fails to make contractual
payments or achieve performance measures.&#160;
The Company has a liability of $17 million on its consolidated balance
sheet at December&nbsp;31, 2005, relating to these guarantees.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">43</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">8</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="12%" colspan="2" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:12.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(5</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0.375pt 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">)</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="43%" valign="top" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:43.0%;">

  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border:none;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.3%;">

  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">291</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">

  </td>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">129</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">52</font></p>

  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">$</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="10%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;border-bottom:double windowtext 1.5pt;border-left:none;border-right:none;border-top:solid windowtext 1.0pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:10.7%;">
  <p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">134</font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="1%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#CCEEFF" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:1.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As discussed
in Note 13. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Income Taxes</font></i>, Kraft has recognized
income tax benefits in the consolidated statements of earnings during 2005 and
2004 as a result of various tax events, including the benefits earned under the
provisions of the American Jobs Creation Act.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><u><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Note 20. Subsequent Event:</font></u></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-27.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In January&nbsp;2006,
the Company announced plans to continue its restructuring efforts beyond those
originally contemplated (see Note 3. <i><font style="font-style:italic;">Asset Impairment, Exit and
Implementation Costs</font></i>).&#160;
Additional pre-tax charges are anticipated to be $2.5 billion from 2006
to 2009, of which approximately $1.6 billion are expected to require cash
payments.&#160; These charges will result in
the anticipated closure of up to 20 additional facilities and the elimination
of approximately 8,000 additional positions.&#160;
Initiatives under the expanded program include additional organizational
streamlining and facility closures.&#160; The
entire restructuring program is expected to ultimately result in $3.7 billion
in pre-tax charges, the closure of up to 40 facilities and the elimination of
approximately 14,000 positions.&#160;
Approximately $2.3 billion of the $3.7 billion in pre-tax charges are
expected to require cash payments.</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">46</font></p>

<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left"></div>
